widgets_values:
## Note about Last Frame:

### New Version:
- Added Automatic Last Frame

### Old version:
For chaining: Set skip_first_images = Length - 1
Examples:
- Length 17  skip 16  saves 16 output frames worth of last frame
- Length 33  skip 32
- Length 65  skip 64
This extracts the final frame for use as the starting image in the next queue.
A cat sunbathing in a french style window

nodes.title: IMPORTANT (OLD)
widgets_values:
### Quick Testing & Scaling Guide

1. **Start small for testing**  
   Generate your first test video at **1 second** (16 output frames at 16 FPS). To achieve this with Wan, set the length to **17** (frame +1 rule).  
   If everything looks good (no errors, decent motion/quality, VRAM stable), gradually increase the length.

2. **How to set the correct number of frames**  
   For Wan workflows:  
   - Set **length = desired output frames + 1** (e.g., for 16 output frames, set length=17).  
   - For extracting the last frame (e.g., for chaining): Set **skip first images = length - 1** (which equals your desired output frames).  
   Examples:  
   - For 16 output frames  set length=17, skip first=16  
   - For 32 output frames  set length=33, skip first=32  
   - For 64 output frames  set length=65, skip first=64  

### Recommended Progression (16 FPS)

| Seconds | Output Frames | Set Length (frames +1) | Skip First for Last Frame (length -1) |
|---------|---------------|-------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| 1       | 16            | 17                      | 16                                    |
| 2       | 32            | 33                      | 32                                    |
| 3       | 48            | 49                      | 48                                    |
| 4       | 64            | 65                      | 64                                    |
| 5       | 80            | 81                      | 80                                    |
| 6       | 96            | 97                      | 96                                    |
| 7       | 112           | 113                     | 112                                   |
| 8       | 128           | 129                     | 128                                   |
| 9       | 144           | 145                     | 144                                   |
| 10      | 160           | 161                     | 160                                   |
| 11      | 176           | 177                     | 176                                   |
| 12      | 192           | 193                     | 192                                   |
| 13      | 208           | 209                     | 208                                   |

Start with length=17 (for 1s/16 frames output)  check output  if stable, step up to 33 (2s/32 frames), then 49, etc.  
This helps you avoid VRAM crashes, long failed generations, and wasted time while dialing in your settings.

nodes.title: MODELS
widgets_values:
## Required Files & Download Links

This workflow uses the **wan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw** GGUF model [Phr00t/befox rapid merge](https://huggingface.co/befox/WAN2.2-14B-Rapid-AllInOne-GGUF) + compatible components.  
All files are free from Hugging Face (no login needed for basic downloads).

### **Important Naming Note**  
Any "D" prefix in filenames (e.g., `Dwamumt5-xxl-encoder-Q3_K.gguf`, `Dwan_2.1_vae.safetensors`, `Dwan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw-Q3_K.gguf`) is **not** part of the original model name.  
It is only how I organize files locally in my ComfyUI `models` folder (inside a "D" subfolder).  
When downloading, use the **exact filenames** shown below (without any "D" prefix). ComfyUI will load them correctly as long as theyre in the right subfolders.

## 1. Main Model (GGUF  choose quant based on your VRAM)
Repo: https://huggingface.co/befox/WAN2.2-14B-Rapid-AllInOne-GGUF/tree/main/v10  
Recommended for low VRAM (68 GB cards): Q3_K or Q4_K  

- Q3_K (~8 GB, very low VRAM friendly):  
  [wan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw-Q3_K.gguf](https://huggingface.co/befox/WAN2.2-14B-Rapid-AllInOne-GGUF/resolve/main/v10/wan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw-Q3_K.gguf?download=true)  

- Q4_K (~910 GB, good balance):  
  [wan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw-Q4_K.gguf](https://huggingface.co/befox/WAN2.2-14B-Rapid-AllInOne-GGUF/resolve/main/v10/wan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw-Q4_K.gguf?download=true)  

- Q5_K (~1112 GB, higher quality):  
  [wan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw-Q5_K.gguf](https://huggingface.co/befox/WAN2.2-14B-Rapid-AllInOne-GGUF/resolve/main/v10/wan2.2-t2v-rapid-aio-v10-nsfw-Q5_K.gguf?download=true)  

**Placement**: `ComfyUI/models/unet` or `models/checkpoints`

## 2. Text Encoder / CLIP (umt5-xxl GGUF  Wan compatible)
Repo: https://huggingface.co/city96/umt5-xxl-encoder-gguf/tree/main  
Recommended: Q3_K_M (lowest VRAM usage, good performance)

- umt5-xxl-encoder-Q3_K_M.gguf (~3 GB):  
  [umt5-xxl-encoder-Q3_K_M.gguf](https://huggingface.co/city96/umt5-xxl-encoder-gguf/resolve/main/umt5-xxl-encoder-Q3_K_M.gguf?download=true)  

Alternative (if you prefer slightly higher quality):  
- umt5-xxl-encoder-Q4_K_M.gguf (~3.7 GB):  
  [umt5-xxl-encoder-Q4_K_M.gguf](https://huggingface.co/city96/umt5-xxl-encoder-gguf/resolve/main/umt5-xxl-encoder-Q4_K_M.gguf?download=true)  

**Placement**: `ComfyUI/models/clip` or `models/text_encoders`  
(Note: My local file is placed in `D\wamumt5-xxl-encoder-Q3_K.gguf`  just a folder prefix.)

## 3. VAE
Repo: https://huggingface.co/Comfy-Org/Wan_2.2_ComfyUI_Repackaged/tree/main/split_files/vae  

- wan_2.1_vae.safetensors (~254 MB):  
  [wan_2.1_vae.safetensors](https://huggingface.co/Comfy-Org/Wan_2.2_ComfyUI_Repackaged/resolve/main/split_files/vae/wan_2.1_vae.safetensors?download=true)  

**Placement**: `ComfyUI/models/vae`  
(Note: My local file is placed in `D\wan_2.1_vae.safetensors`  again, just my folder prefix.)

### Quick Tips
- Verify file hashes after download (Hugging Face shows them on each file page).  
- If links change, search Hugging Face for WAN2.2-14B-Rapid-AllInOne-GGUF (befox), umt5-xxl-encoder-gguf (city96), or Wan_2.2_ComfyUI_Repackaged (Comfy-Org).  
- For best low-VRAM performance: Use Q3_K/Q4_K model + Q3_K_M CLIP + the standard Wan VAE.
